The true story of how a couple of people, a bunch of partners and an AI assistant rewrote the rules of maritime equipment classification — in five weeks, for less than €40.
Project story
How it happened
Every ship in the world carries a list of its equipment, coded to a standard called SFI. But SFI was last updated before the offshore revolution, before emissions regulations rewrote the rules of marine engineering, before anyone had ever classified a carbon capture system or a deep-water ROV. The gap between what ships now carry and what the standard describes had become impossible to ignore.
📋 Background note
The SFI Group System was born in 1972 as a Norwegian research project. As it spread globally, the maintenance and ownership of the standard was progressively transferred to SpecTec, which today is its official owner — responsible for development, licensing and rights protection.
